<paragraph blockId="49.[151,1436,1776,1869]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,345,1776,1800]" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">FIGURES 80–86</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1931" box="[361,599,1777,1800]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendozana">
<emphasis box="[361,599,1777,1800]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Leptocera mendozana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Argentina). Male terminalia (phallus and postgonites omitted): (80) lateral; (81) posterior; (82) ventral; (83) sternite 5. Female terminalia: (84) dorsal; (85) spermathecae; (86) ventral. da—desclerotized area, sa—shining area of tergite 7.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,383,409]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Distribution</emphasis>
. An uncommon Andean species that ranges from Lake Titicaca in 
<collectingCountry box="[1165,1220,384,410]" name="Peru" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Peru</collectingCountry>
/ 
<collectingCountry box="[1229,1313,384,410]" name="Bolivia" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
to central 
<collectingCountry box="[151,268,422,448]" name="Argentina" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[287,519,422,448]" country="Argentina" name="Mendoza" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Mendoza Province</collectingRegion>
). The elevation range covered by this species (
<quantity box="[1097,1259,422,448]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.225" metricValueMax="3.8" metricValueMin="0.65" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" unit="m" value="2225.0" valueMax="3800.0" valueMin="650.0">650–3,800 m</quantity>
) is one of the greatest in New World 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Olivier" authorityYear="1813" box="[422,541,461,486]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[422,541,461,486]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Leptocera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,331,499,525]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Discussion</emphasis>
. This species and the allopatric 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1931" box="[708,914,500,525]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neocurvinervis">
<emphasis box="[708,914,500,525]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">L. neocurvinervis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the only species in the 
<taxonomicName box="[1233,1360,500,525]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caenosa">
<emphasis box="[1233,1360,500,525]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">L. caenosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (except the 
<taxonomicName box="[293,485,538,563]" class="Bryopsida" family="Ditrichaceae" genus="Skottsbergia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Dicranales" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="cultellipennis">
<emphasis box="[293,485,538,563]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">L. cultellipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup from Robinson Crusoe I.), in which male sternite 5 possesses a pale desclerotized area in front of the field of enlarged microtrichia (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1931" box="[977,1146,577,602]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendozana">
<emphasis box="[977,1146,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">L. mendozana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
this field is bare, in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neocurvinervis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">L. neocurvinervis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is microtrichose). Diagnostic for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1931" box="[740,904,616,641]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendozana">
<emphasis box="[740,904,616,641]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">L. mendozana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the simple male cercus (lacking lamellate medial process) and the produced ventromedial corner of the posterior section of the surstylus, which is armed with an additional spine-like bristle (besides the usual two, more lateral bristles). The female has few distinctive features. It differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Buck &amp; Marshall, 2009" authorityName="Buck &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2009" box="[558,762,732,757]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neocurvinervis" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[558,762,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">L. neocurvinervis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[769,825,732,758]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
by the bumpy surface of the spermathecae and from 
<taxonomicName authority="Buck &amp; Marshall, 2009" authorityName="Buck &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2009" box="[151,308,770,795]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="papallacta" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[151,308,770,795]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">L. papallacta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[318,373,770,796]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
by the (usually) shorter bristle above the distal dorsal mid tibial bristle (both species are also darker than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1931" box="[345,509,809,834]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendozana">
<emphasis box="[345,509,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">L. mendozana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
